##### MF1: GENERAL INFORMATION                                    6329 1451  189
                                                                  6329 1451  190
- MT451    : Descriptive data and directory                       6329 1451  191
                                                                  6329 1451  192
This text and the full directory of used MF/MT sections.          6329 1451  193
                                                                  6329 1451  194
##### MF2: RESONANCE PARAMETERS                                   6329 1451  195
                                                                  6329 1451  196
- MT151    : Resonance parameters                                 6329 1451  197
                                                                  6329 1451  198
Details about the origin of the resonance parameters for this     6329 1451  199
nuclide are given above in this description. In general, both a   6329 1451  200
Resolved and an Unresolved Resonance Range are given.             6329 1451  201
                                                                  6329 1451  202
##### MF3: REACTION CROSS SECTIONS                                6329 1451  203
                                                                  6329 1451  204
All the data present in the following MT-sections have been       6329 1451  205
calculated with TALYS, possibly normalized to experimental data.  6329 1451  206
If the maximal cross section in an excitation function over the   6329 1451  207
whole energy range does not exceed 1.e-9 b, the MT-number is not  6329 1451  208
included. Cross sections lower than 1.e-20 b are assumed to have  6329 1451  209
no physical meaning and are set to zero. All MT numbers extend up 6329 1451  210
to the highest incident energy.                                   6329 1451  211
The following reaction channels/MT numbers are generally included:6329 1451  212
                                                                  6329 1451  213
- MT1      : Total cross section                                  6329 1451  214
                                                                  6329 1451  215
Calculated with the optical model over the whole energy range,    6329 1451  216
or partly reproduced using experimental data.                     6329 1451  217
                                                                  6329 1451  218
- MT2      : Elastic scattering cross section                     6329 1451  219
                                                                  6329 1451  220
Obtained by subtracting the non-elastic cross section from the    6329 1451  221
total cross section.                                              6329 1451  222
                                                                  6329 1451  223
- MT3      : Non-elastic cross section                            6329 1451  224
                                                                  6329 1451  225
Calculated with the optical model over the whole energy range.    6329 1451  226
                                                                  6329 1451  227
- MT4      : Total inelastic cross section                        6329 1451  228
                                                                  6329 1451  229
Sum of MT=51-91.                                                  6329 1451  230
                                                                  6329 1451  231
- MT5      : (n,anything) cross section                           6329 1451  232
                                                                  6329 1451  233
MT5 contains the reactions which can not be stored in any other   6329 1451  234
MT-number. The information of MF3/MT5 can be combined with        6329 1451  235
MF6/MT5 to obtain residual production cross sections particle     6329 1451  236
production cross sections and (double-)differential cross         6329 1451  237
sections.                                                         6329 1451  238
                                                                  6329 1451  239
- MT16     : (n,2n) cross section                                 6329 1451  240
- MT17     : (n,3n) cross section                                 6329 1451  241
- MT22     : (n,na) cross section                                 6329 1451  242
- MT28     : (n,np) cross section                                 6329 1451  243
- MT51-90  : (n,n') cross section for 1st-40th excited state      6329 1451  244
- MT91     : (n,n') continuum cross section                       6329 1451  245
- MT102    : (n,gamma) cross section                              6329 1451  246
- MT103    : (n,p) cross section                                  6329 1451  247
- MT104    : (n,d) cross section                                  6329 1451  248
- MT105    : (n,t) cross section                                  6329 1451  249
- MT106    : (n,h) cross section                                  6329 1451  250
- MT107    : (n,a) cross section                                  6329 1451  251
- MT600-610: (n,p) cross section for 0th-10th excited state       6329 1451  252
- MT649    : (n,p) continuum cross section                        6329 1451  253
- MT650-655: (n,d) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        6329 1451  254
- MT699    : (n,d) continuum cross section                        6329 1451  255
- MT700-705: (n,t) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        6329 1451  256
- MT749    : (n,t) continuum cross section                        6329 1451  257
- MT750-755: (n,h) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        6329 1451  258
- MT799    : (n,h) continuum cross section                        6329 1451  259
- MT800-810: (n,a) cross section for 0th-10th excited state       6329 1451  260
- MT849    : (n,a) continuum cross section                        6329 1451  261
                                                                  6329 1451  262
##### MF4: ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS OF SECONDARY PARTICLES           6329 1451  263
                                                                  6329 1451  264
We use MF4 for the neutron scattering angular distribution for    6329 1451  265
discrete levels.                                                  6329 1451  266
                                                                  6329 1451  267
- MT2      : Elastic angular distribution                         6329 1451  268
                                                                  6329 1451  269
The flag LTT=3 is used to indicate a switch at some high energy,  6329 1451  270
generally 50 MeV, from a Legendre representation to a tabulated   6329 1451  271
representation. For incident energies below this energy, the      6329 1451  272
Legendre coefficients are given on a sufficiently precise energy  6329 1451  273
grid. They are a sum of calculated Legendre coefficients for      6329 1451  274
compound nucleus and shape-elastic scattering. For higher         6329 1451  275
incident energies, relative angular distributions are tabulated   6329 1451  276
on an angular grid.                                               6329 1451  277
                                                                  6329 1451  278
- MT51-70  : (n,n') angular distribution for 1st-20th state       6329 1451  279
- MT600-610: (n,p) angular distribution for 0th-10th state        6329 1451  280
- MT650-655: (n,d) angular distribution for 0th-5th state         6329 1451  281
- MT700-705: (n,t) angular distribution for 0th-5th state         6329 1451  282
- MT750-755: (n,h) angular distribution for 0th-5th state         6329 1451  283
- MT800-810: (n,a) angular distribution for 0th-10th state        6329 1451  284
                                                                  6329 1451  285
##### MF6: PRODUCT ENERGY-ANGLE DISTRIBUTIONS                     6329 1451  286
                                                                  6329 1451  287
In MF6 we store all secondary energy, angle, and energy-angle     6329 1451  288
distributions, as well as all residual and discrete + continuum   6329 1451  289
photon production cross sections for channels other than capture  6329 1451  290
(MT102) and reactions to discrete levels (MT51,etc.).             6329 1451  291
All data are generated with TALYS.                                6329 1451  292
                                                                  6329 1451  293
- MT5      : (n,anything) yields and energy-angle distributions   6329 1451  294
                                                                  6329 1451  295
MT5 contains, in this order,                                      6329 1451  296
For neutrons up to alpha particles and photons:                   6329 1451  297
- the production yields per particle for the whole energy range   6329 1451  298
- the secondary energy-angle distributions per particles which are6329 1451  299
  not represented by explicit MT numbers. On a secondary energy   6329 1451  300
  grid the relative emission spectra are given together with the  6329 1451  301
  parameters for the Kalbach systematics for angular              6329 1451  302
  distributions. Inelastic scattering cross sections for discrete 6329 1451  303
  states have been broadened and added to the continuum spectra.  6329 1451  304
For each residual product:                                        6329 1451  305
- the production yields for the whole energy range.               6329 1451  306
- the recoil                                                      6329 1451  307
These distributions can be multiplied with MF3/MT5 to get         6329 1451  308
the production cross sections and (double-)differential cross     6329 1451  309
sections.                                                         6329 1451  310
                                                                  6329 1451  311
- MT16     : (n,2n) energy-angle distr. and photon production     6329 1451  312
                                                                  6329 1451  313
First, for each type of outgoing particle, the (trivial) integer  6329 1451  314
particle yields are given. Next, on a sufficiently dense incident 6329 1451  315
energy grid the secondary energy-angle distributions are          6329 1451  316
specified by means of the relative emission spectra and the       6329 1451  317
parameters for the Kalbach systematics for angular distributions. 6329 1451  318
Next, the photon yield is tabulated as a function of incident     6329 1451  319
energy. For each incident energy, the photon production is given  6329 1451  320
for all discrete gamma lines present in the final nucleus. A      6329 1451  321
continuum photon distribution is added to this. We assume         6329 1451  322
isotropy for all produced gamma rays.                             6329 1451  323
                                                                  6329 1451  324
For the following MT-numbers, the same procedure as for MT16 is   6329 1451  325
followed:                                                         6329 1451  326
                                                                  6329 1451  327
- MT17 : (n,3n) energy-angle distr. and photon production         6329 1451  328
- MT22 : (n,na) energy-angle distr. and photon production         6329 1451  329
- MT28 : (n,np) energy-angle distr. and photon production         6329 1451  330
- MT91 : (n,n') continuum energy-angle distr. and phot. prod.     6329 1451  331
- MT649: (n,p) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     6329 1451  332
- MT699: (n,d) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     6329 1451  333
- MT749: (n,t) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     6329 1451  334
- MT809: (n,h) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     6329 1451  335
- MT849: (n,a) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     6329 1451  336
                                                                  6329 1451  337
##### MF8: RADIOACTIVE DECAY DATA                                 6329 1451  338
                                                                  6329 1451  339
For reactions to isomers, MF8 designates where the information    6329 1451  340
for isomeric versus ground state production, or residual          6329 1451  341
production can be found, i.e. for each MT number it points to     6329 1451  342
either MF6, MF9 or MF10.                                          6329 1451  343
                                                                  6329 1451  344
##### MF9: MULTIPLICITIES FOR PRODUCTION OF RADIOACTIVE NUCLIDES  6329 1451  345
                                                                  6329 1451  346
MF9 is used for isomer production by non-threshold reactions.     6329 1451  347
Final states with a lifetime that exceeds 1 second are treated    6329 1451  348
as isomer.                                                        6329 1451  349
                                                                  6329 1451  350
##### MF10: CROSS SECTIONS FOR PRODUCTION OF RADIOACTIVE NUCLIDES 6329 1451  351
                                                                  6329 1451  352
MF10 is used for isomer production by threshold reactions.        6329 1451  353
Final states with a lifetime that exceeds 1 second are treated    6329 1451  354
as isomer.                                                        6329 1451  355
                                                                  6329 1451  356
##### MF12: PHOTON PRODUCTION YIELD DATA                          6329 1451  357
                                                                  6329 1451  358
MF12 is used for the photon production for two types of reactions:6329 1451  359
- Reactions to discrete levels (MT51, etc.) For this transition   6329 1451  360
  probabilities are used (LO=2)                                   6329 1451  361
- Photons from neutron capture (MT102). Here multiplicities are   6329 1451  362
  given                                                           6329 1451  363
                                                                  6329 1451  364
##### MF14: PHOTON ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS                          6329 1451  365
                                                                  6329 1451  366
All photon production is considered as isotropic                  6329 1451  367
                                                                  6329 1451  368
##### MF15: PHOTON ENERGY SPECTRA                                 6329 1451  369
                                                                  6329 1451  370
For capture (MT102), the photon energy spectrum is given.         6329 1451  371
                                                                  6329 1451  372
##### MF32: COVARIANCES OF RESONANCE PARAMETERS                   6329 1451  373
                                                                  6329 1451  374
In MF32, we store the covariances of resonance parameters,        6329 1451  375
and more details are given above in this description.             6329 1451  376
                                                                  6329 1451  377
##### MF33: COVARIANCES OF NEUTRON CROSS SECTIONS                 6329 1451  378
                                                                  6329 1451  379
In MF33, we store the covariances of most, but not all, reaction  6329 1451  380
channels that are given in MF3. All covariances are generated     6329 1451  381
with the TASMAN code [kon12], which generates TALYS runs using    6329 1451  382
a Monte Carlo parameter method.                                   6329 1451  383
For each MT-number, the information consists of:                  6329 1451  384
1. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTa, Ea (variances)                6329 1451  385
2. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTa, Eb (correlations for the      6329 1451  386
   same reaction channel between different energies)              6329 1451  387
3. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTb, Ea (correlations between      6329 1451  388
   different reaction channels for the same energy)               6329 1451  389
4. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTb, Eb (correlations between      6329 1451  390
   different reaction channels for different energies)            6329 1451  391
Classes 1 and 2 are covered by NI-type subsubsections with        6329 1451  392
flag LB=5, followed by a LB=8 section which contains              6329 1451  393
the cross section variances multiplied by 1.e-3. Next, classes 3  6329 1451  394
and 4 are covered by flag LB=6 to account for the different       6329 1451  395
energy grids that two correlating MT-sections may have. Since     6329 1451  396
the total correlation matrix is fully symmetric, we only need to  6329 1451  397
include the correlation elements between different MT-numbers     6329 1451  398
once, and we do that in the subsection with the lowest of the     6329 1451  399
two MT-numbers. We include covariance information for all the     6329 1451  400
total cross sections, the lumped partial cross sections and the   6329 1451  401
individual inelastic cross sections per level (MT51,...). We do   6329 1451  402
not include covariances for MT600 and higher MT-numbers. For the  6329 1451  403
most important channels, we include cross-channel correlations.   6329 1451  404
                                                                  6329 1451  405
##### MF34: COVARIANCES OF ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS                  6329 1451  406
                                                                  6329 1451  407
In MF34, we store the covariances of the elastic scattering       6329 1451  408
angular distributions that are given in MF4/MT2. All covariances  6329 1451  409
are generated with the TASMAN code [kon12], which generates       6329 1451  410
TALYS runs using a Monte Carlo parameter method. The tables are   6329 1451  411
restricted to MT2 and contain covariances for the first 6         6329 1451  412
Legendre coefficients. Both intra- and inter-correlations of the  6329 1451  413
various Legendre coefficients are given. As in MF33, the LB5      6329 1451  414
representation is used.                                           6329 1451  415
                                                                  6329 1451  416
##### MF40: COVARIANCES OF ISOMER PRODUCTION                      6329 1451  417
                                                                  6329 1451  418
For covariances of ground state and isomeric cross sections, the  6329 1451  419
same procedures as for MF33 are used.                             6329 1451  420
                                                                  6329 1451  421
